Package edu.cmu.cs.plural.annot

This package contains annotations used by the Plural object protocol checker.

See:
          Description

Interface Summary
PluralAnalysis This interface collects string constants for Plural's analysis names.
 

Enum Summary
Use This enumeration distinguishes the allowed uses of a permission: Dynamic dispatch (only): DISPATCH Field access (only): FIELDS Both: DISP_FIELDS This is primarily interesting to distinguish receiver permissions of instance methods; permissions for other objects are usually (implicitly) dispatch-only.
 

Annotation Types Summary
Capture Annotate objects that are captured by the result of a method or constructor with this annotation.
Cases Use this annotation to define multiple method cases (pairs of required and ensured permissions) for a single method.
ClassStates A prototype of state invariants, this class allows you to declare a set of mutually exclusive states, and the invariants that they imply (if any) on fields of the class they describe.
FalseIndicates This annotation can be used to define the state indicated by the false result of a boolean state test.
Full Full permissions grant exclusive modifying access but allow other permissions to read from the same object.
Fulls Aggregator for Full annotations.
Imm Immutable permissions grant read-only access and guarantee that no modifications to the referenced object will be made.
Imms Aggregator for Imm annotations.
IsResult Mark a method parameter with this annotation that is known to be the result of the method.
Lend Annotate objects that lend the result of a method with this annotation.
NoEffects Marker annotation for pure methods.
NonReentrant Marker annotation for non-reentrant types.
Param Placed on a class or interface, this annotation defines a parameter, similar to a specification field in behavioral specification approaches.
Perm This is a general permission annotation for a method.
Pure Pure permissions grant read-only access but assume that other permissions are allowed to modify the referenced object.
Pures Aggregator for Pure annotations.
Range This is an annotation to restrict possible values of an int or char; it is currently not supported.
Refine This is a container annotation to hold States annotations.
Release Use this annotation to indicate parameter permissions released by the annotated object.
ResultFull Use this annotation to indicate that the returned permission of a method is Full.
ResultImm Use this annotation to indicate that the returned permission of a method is Imm.
ResultPure Use this annotation to indicate that the returned permission of a method is Pure.
ResultShare Use this annotation to indicate that the returned permission of a method is Share.
ResultUnique Use this annotation to indicate that the returned permission of a method is Unique.
Share Share permissions grant modifying access but assume that other references might modify the referenced object as well.
Shares Aggregator for Share annotations.
State Another prototype interface, this one allows us to declare individual states and the state invariants that they have.
States This annotation is used to declare a set of mutually exclusive states.
TrueIndicates This annotation can be used to define the state indicated by the true result of a boolean state test.
Unique Unique permissions guarantee that no other permissions for the same object exist.
Uniques Aggregator for Unique annotations.
 

Package edu.cmu.cs.plural.annot Description

This package contains annotations used by the Plural object protocol checker. To get started, you can take a look at the annotations for associating a permission with a method receiver or parameter, including Unique, Full, Share, Imm, and Pure. Perm lets you specify more complicated methods. Invariants are defined using State on classes. States lets you define states explicitly, e.g., in an interface. Finally, a set of annotations for conveying aliasing information is available, e.g. Capture and IsResult.
